{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Log entries with the same trace ID are grouped together regardless of which microservice emitted them.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failures are most likely at module handoff boundaries (JSON parse/normalize -> correlation/grouping), especially when service-specific schemas map trace IDs differently. A pure unit test of grouping logic can miss those wiring issues.","test_description":"Feed mixed log batches from multiple service emitters through the real ingest+parse+normalize+group pipeline (in-process, no network). Assert one correlated group per trace ID across services and no cross-trace contamination.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The timeline view orders entries by timestamp, correctly handling clock skew of up to 500ms between services.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This depends on how correlation data and timestamp normalization/skew-tolerance logic interact. Unit tests of sorting alone can miss failures introduced by upstream timestamp parsing or skew compensation wiring.","test_description":"Run end-to-end local timeline assembly with logs from multiple services whose timestamps are intentionally offset within +/-500ms. Verify final timeline order reflects causal request progression under the skew policy.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A latency spike (p99 above 3x the baseline) is detected and flagged in the anomaly report.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is typically between metric aggregation (baseline + percentile windowing) and anomaly rule evaluation/reporting. Mocking either side can hide threshold and window alignment bugs.","test_description":"Execute the real local stats pipeline on synthetic time windows: stable baseline traffic followed by elevated latency outliers that push p99 above 3x baseline. Assert anomaly flag appears with correct metric context in the report.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Malformed JSON log entries are skipped without crashing the pipeline, and the count of skipped entries is reported.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Crash-resilience and skipped-count reporting span parser error handling, pipeline continuation, and reporting counters. A parser-only unit test would not prove pipeline survivability or accurate aggregate counts.","test_description":"Process a mixed batch with valid and malformed JSON records through the full local ingest pipeline. Assert processing completes, valid entries are still emitted, malformed ones are skipped, and skipped-count equals malformed input count.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The tool handles a burst of 10,000 log entries per second without dropping entries or falling behind.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is a throughput/SLO behavior dependent on runtime scheduling, memory pressure, queue backpressure, and wall-clock timing. In-process mocks can pass while real OS/runtime behavior drops events or accumulates lag.","test_description":"Run a load test against the real executable/process with a burst generator producing 10,000 entries/sec for a fixed interval. Measure ingest vs processed counts, queue depth/lag, and end-state drain time; fail on drops or sustained backlog growth.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.85,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
